## 1. Purpose
This document defines the boundaries and applicability of [COMPANY]'s Information Security Management System (ISMS): the systems, data, locations, people, and processes that the ISMS governs, and those explicitly excluded. It exists to give assessors, leadership, and workforce an unambiguous statement of what is protected, and to serve as the authoritative basis for the Statement of Applicability (`statement-of-applicability.md.template`) and the HITRUST scoping exercise.

## 2. Scope
This statement applies to the entire ISMS as approved by [CEO / Board]. It governs the determination of in-scope and out-of-scope assets and is binding on all workforce members and contractors who interact with in-scope systems or data. The scope is set with reference to the requirements of interested parties (`../risk/risk-management-methodology.md.template`), the regulatory obligations tracked in `../compliance/legal-and-regulatory-compliance.md.template`, and the business objective of achieving and maintaining HITRUST certification.

## 3. Policy
1. The ISMS scope **shall** be formally defined, documented in this statement, and approved by [CEO / Board] before any HITRUST assessment or SoA finalization.
2. The scope **shall** explicitly enumerate the in-scope systems, data types, physical and logical locations, organizational units, and people, and **shall** state material exclusions with justification.
3. All systems that create, receive, maintain, or transmit PHI **shall** be in scope; PHI may not be excluded from the ISMS.
4. Interfaces and dependencies between in-scope and out-of-scope elements **shall** be identified so that boundary controls can be applied.
5. The scope **shall** be reviewed at least annually at management review (`management-review.md.template`) and re-confirmed upon any significant change to architecture, data flows, hosting, acquisitions, or the regulatory environment.
6. Any change to scope **shall** be managed as a change to the ISMS, re-approved by the [Approver], and reflected in the SoA and affected policies.

## 4. Roles & Responsibilities
| Role | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| [CEO / Board] | Approves the ISMS scope and any subsequent changes. |
| [Security Officer / CISO] | Owns this statement; proposes scope; maintains the system/data inventory mapping. |
| [Privacy Officer] | Confirms all PHI flows are captured in scope. |
| Engineering / Platform Leads | Confirm system inventory, data flows, and dependencies are accurate. |
| All Workforce | Operate only in-scope systems for in-scope activities per policy. |

See `roles-and-responsibilities.md.template` for full role definitions.

